:''[[Ostanes (spider)|Ostanes]]'' is also a spider genus ([[Thomisidae]]).

'''Osthanes''' or '''Ostanes''' is the name given to a [[Persian]]<ref>Problems of Mysticism and Its Symbolism; By Herbert Silberer; Page 136;</ref> [[Zoroastrian]] [[Magi|magus]], [[Astrology|astrologer]] and [[Alchemy|alchemist]]. Though a number of historical "Ostanes" figures are mentioned in ancient texts,<ref>Such as a son of [[Darius II of Persia|Darius II]]; a mage accompanying [[Alexander the Great|Alexander]] to India; a mage accompanying [[Xerxes]] during his expedition to [[Greece]] (also a legendary teacher of [[Democritus]]).</ref> it is unknown which one might have served as the basis for the legendary Ostanes.

[[Pliny the Elder]] identified him as the first person to write a treatise on magic. Similarly, various Hellenistic and Roman writers, based on Hellenistic texts attributed to him, regarded him as an authority on [[alchemy]], [[necromancy]], [[divination]]. His alchemical authority continued in medieval times as he is frequently cited in [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] alchemical literature, such as an Arabic treatise titled ''Kitab al-Fusul al-ithnay <U+2018>ashar fi 'ilm al-hajar al-mukarram'' (The Book of the Twelve Chapters on the Honourable Stone).

==As the teacher of Democritus==
He was the teacher of [[Democritus]]<ref>http://www.thedyinggod.com/mithraism_alchemy.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.jwmt.org/v2n13/sign.html</ref><ref>http://www.granta.demon.co.uk/arsm/jg/hermes.html</ref><ref>http://homepages.tscnet.com/omard1/o.htm</ref><ref>http://www.askwhy.co.uk/christianity/0617Magic.php</ref><ref>http://www.thedyinggod.com/chaldeanmagi/index.html</ref><ref>The Dying God: The Hidden History of Western Civilization By David Livingstone, page 218</ref><ref>Tradition, Transmission, Transformation: Proceedings of Two Conferences, page 175</ref><ref>[http://www.encyclopediairanica.com/articles/sup/Ostanes.html  Encylopedia Iranica]</ref><ref>http://www.skepticfiles.org/mys1/aggrpa.htm</ref><ref>http://www.wicca-chat.com/naturalmagic/natural1.htm</ref><ref>The Philological Museum, Page 11</ref><ref>Thrice Greatest Hermes
 By G. R. S. Mead, page 195</ref>. Democritus' father was so wealthy, that it was said that he received [[Xerxes]] ([[Persian]] Emperor) on his march through Abdera. Osthanes introduced the [[Persian philosophy]] and thoughts of [[Zoroaster]], as well as [[chemistry]] ([[alchemy]]) to him.

